From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 11:26:04 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] kati: consider rule-less prerequisites LAZILY, like GNU make
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

A rule-less prerequisite that doesn't exist yet was existence-checked
the moment the scheduler saw it (it has no deps, so it entered the
ready heap at t=0) — but GNU checks it only when its CONSUMER is
considered, by which time an earlier recipe may have created the file
as an undeclared side effect, or an earlier sub-make may have built
it. Classic kbuild/link-tree pattern; surfaced as ordering-dependent
'No rule to make target .../library.so' on a real build.

prepare_node now defers: the missing rule-less node completes quietly
into a 'missing' set; each consumer re-stats its missing deps when IT
is prepared (folding a fresh mtime into the staleness compare) and
only errors — with the rejection/provenance notes — if the file STILL
doesn't exist. Goal targets that end the build still-missing keep the
plain 'No rule to make target' error. Corpus case pins the
side-effect ordering shape against GNU; both corpora fail=0.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01B97aMMA3rHQW7gsyBB2Cpa
